deck: Owner of the mystical Black Box of secrets, Laurence Cooper manipulate the purple plasma to protect the world from the forces of darkness.
description:
Background

Black Box was created as analog of Green Lantern Alan Scott by Mark Millar to be used during the River Run arc in Millar's Swamp Thing run. Set in a metafiction inside the story, the character was an stand-in for the golden age Green Lantern because of the Vertigo-mainstream DC characters restriction working on that time. Millar also would use other analogs for DC characters such as the Traveller (stand-in for Phantom Stranger) and the Word (an Spectre replacement).

History

Laurence Cooper became the Black Box when a mysterious black box materialized in his cellar. Using the box as a power source and channeling in a power staff as a purple plasma, Cooper fought against the forces of darkness even beyond which includes Solomon Grundy.

Twenty years later, Cooper prime time has passed and now he lives a retired live along with his wife, Anna, in the city of Moline, mourning his lost son, Michael, a kid born with a neurological disease and who was suppously kidnapped by unknown persons

. One last adventure would put him against a resurrected Solomon Grundy, (really, a body possesed by the Swamp Thing) who has raised in Slaughter Swamp. Confident in his power will protect him, Laurence went to stop Grundy, but he fond himself overpowered by the elementally driven Grundy. Using his staff to discover the secret of the swamp, Black Box freed all the spirits trapped in the swamp, the soul of people killed and bodies buried in the dark waters. One of those bodies was the corpse of his son Michael. He discovered then it was his wife who killed his son, because she couldn't endure more the situation. She had to live with the kid alll the time meanwhile his father was far from home, in superheroic adventures. So she lied about the kidnapping and never said anything about that but she was all her life regreting her actions. The Black Box in a last effort send all the spirits to the other life and let the Swamp Thing continue his traveling.

For him however, he discoverd than not even magic could protect him from the secrets hide in his own home.

Powers

His powers, which are otherwise identical to golden age Green Lantern's (with a touch of Starman and Doctor Fate), but with a purple plasma instead green, do not effect organic matter (as opposed to merely wood).

deck: She is the daughter of the super-villain, the Master Jailer. She is always desperate to gain his attention.
description:
Carla Draper is the daughter of Carl Draper, also know as Master Jailer and like her father she is a genius who is able to create traps that have come close to defeating the mightiest of heroes.

Carla started her super-villain career as a way to gain her father's attention. She first stolen Carl Draper's Deathtrap program, and rebranded Locksmith. As Locksmith, Carla caught Superman (in his blue energy form) in an "energy hobble" for a brief period. Superman didn't suspect than it was another person behind the hologram and her father was unaware of this.

Carla Draper made an appearance in Superboy #26, under the name Snare. She responded to a request from the Hawaiian Special Crimes Unit to Draper Security for assistance in capturing the super-villain Knockout, who was on the run with a misguided Superboy in tow. Snare, aware of her father's obsession, tried to prove she could do something he could not by capturing Superboy. This led to a fight with the SCU, during which Superboy and Knockout escaped.

When Draper was "recruited" by Checkmate as Castelian, a mysterious hacker almost defeated the castle defenses. Draper hide the fact than his daughter was his main suspect of the attack.

deck: Robin Hood in a Glass Bowl
description:
Origin

The Moon Man was a weird figure who wore costume consisting of a black robe, black gloves topped by a spherical helmet made of slightly mottled one-way glass, so that it resembled the moon, that prevented anyone from seeing his face while letting him see clearly.

He was really Detective-Sergeant Stephen Thatcher who was also the son of the Chief of Police of the city where he lived.

As the Moon Man Thatcher acted as a modern day Robin Hood, stealing from wealthy criminals (and usually leaving them dead) and giving to the poor.

Creators

The Moon Man first appeared in Ten Detective Aces magazine, published by A.A. Wyn's Ace Magazines, The 38 short stories were written by Frederick C. Davis between 1933 and 1937.

Ace Magazine also published a number of comics during the 40’s, while they never published a Moon Man character the first story in the Pulp series, "The Sinister Sphere" was used as the basis for The Raven in Shure-Fire Comics.

However recently Airship 27 has produced a comic book adventure for the glass helmeted Moon Man.
name: The Moon Man

deck: Seeing her family killed by the Crossed, Tiffany ran away and was taken in by the psychiatrist Jack. She took a liking to Jack younger brother Clancy, who was a member of the Crossed.
description:
Origin

Tiffany saw her family being killed by the Crossed. She ran away and was taken in by the young psychiatrist Jack. She lived with Jack for a for weeks when his younger brother Clancy came to Jack, offering Jack a chance to examine the Crossed, thus hoping to find a cure. Now turned into the Crossed, Clancy is locked up inside Jack's house. Tiffany took a perverted liking to Clancy, who initially remained silent when she was within earshot.

As Jack discovered her masturbating on the other side of the door of Clancy's hastily made prison, she and Jack got into an argument. Tiffany wanted to leave the house but the street was full of Crossed. Feeling guilty, Jack offered Tiffany to distract the Crossed so she could escape safely. Jack confronted Clancy one more time. It was at that moment that Clancy revealed that he was molested as a child by Jack himself. Hearing this, Tiffany got angry and backed away from Jack when he approached her. He finally pushed her out the front door, where she was grabbed by the Crossed.
name: Tiffany

deck: Jack is an aspiring psychiatrist. He's the older brother of Clancy, who is now a Crossed victim and his first patient.
description:
Origin

As the oldest child in a fatherless family, Jack quickly became the man in the house. He was polite and eager to please his mother. His younger brother Clancy however, was a real problem child. Jack became a young psychiatrist. When the Crossed virus hit, he got a message from his brother he hadn't seen for six years. Clancy drove to his brother's house with a young woman who had become a Crossed victim. Clancy offered his brother Jack to become his first Crossed patient. Thus offering Jack a chance at the thought process of the Crossed, hoping to find a cure, or at least an explanation, for their actions.

As Jack discovered his housemate Tiffany masturbating on the other side of the door of Clancy's hastily made prison, he and Tiffany got into an argument. Tiffany wanted to leave the house but the street was full of Crossed. Feeling guilty, Jack offered Tiffany to distract the Crossed so she could escape safely. Jack confronted Clancy one more time. It was at that moment that Clancy revealed that he was molested as a child by Jack himself. Hearing this, Tiffany got angry and backed away from Jack when he approached her. He finally pushed her out the front door, where she was grabbed by the Crossed. Jack then opened Clancy's prison and sat down next to him, waiting for the end to come.
name: Jack

deck: The younger brother of Jack and a real problem child. Sacrificed himself to be the patient for his brother Jack, who is a psychiatrist.
description:
Origin

The younger brother of Jack, Clancy has always been a problem child. At the age of 15, he had collected three arrests for vandalism and public lewdness. He made Jack's life miserable whenever he could. On his 18th birthday, Clancy moved out of his parental house. He drank his life away and used drugs. When the Crossed virus hit the world, he reconnected with his brother. He drove to his brother's house with a young woman who had become a Crossed victim. He offered his brother Jack, now an aspiring psychiatrist, to become his first Crossed patient. Thus offering Jack a chance at the thought process of the Crossed, hoping to find a cure, or at least an explanation, for their actions.

Jack's housemate Tiffany took a perverted liking to Clancy. As Jack discovered her masturbating on the other side of the door of Clancy's hastily made prison, she and Jack got into an argument. Tiffany wanted to leave the house but the street was full of Crossed. Feeling guilty, Jack offered Tiffany to distract the Crossed so she could escape safely. Jack confronted Clancy one more time. It was at that moment that Clancy revealed that he was molested as a child by Jack himself. Hearing this, Tiffany got angry and backed away from Jack when he approached her. He finally pushed her out the front door, where she was grabbed by the Crossed. Jack then opened Clancy's prison and sat down next to him, waiting for the end to come.
name: Clancy

Origin

Just after the outbreak of the Crossed virus, everyone went crazy and started looting, looking for food and other survival stuff. Leaving his wife and kids at the house, Russ began looting too. When he returned, his front door was open. His wife was banging the neighbor outside on the lawn. Russ killed the neighbor with his axe, but his wife had already become infected. Afraid, Russ ran away, leaving his kids to fend on their own.

Now trapped on part of a collapsed bridge, Russ formed a group with the other people that got stuck. Fortunately, they were cut off from the Crossed virus. One day, they were visited by survivalists Morgan and Olivia, who divided the group into smaller pieces so they could manage them.

Morgan and Olivia sowed doubt and anger into the group. They convinced Russ that Richard, the self-appointed leader, could better be removed from the group. Russ pushed Richard off the bridge, hoping to kill him. Russ was later bashed his head in by Tyree during a heated argument.

deck: A supernatural entity and member of the Trinity of Sin, cursed to wander the Earth tormented by the mystery of his own identity
description:
This article is about the current Question. For the first person to use the name Question, see Vic Sage. For the second Question, see Renee Montoya.

Origin

Almost nothing is known about the Question or his origin. At some point, probably in the distant past, an unnamed person of unclear origin committed some unknown crime or crimes, apparently the worst of any crimes any being has ever committed. For this, and his ultimate refusal to repent before the Council of Eternity, he was sentenced to wander the Earth forever with neither face nor memory to provide any indication of his transgressions. He travels, lost and tormented by the ultimate question: who am I?

Creation

The Question was created by Geoff Johns and Ethan Van Sciver, making his first appearance in Justice League #0. This character was split from the original Question, who was created by Steve Ditko, and made his first appearance in Blue Beetle #1.

Character Evolution

Post-Flashpoint

The Question was originally the superhero alter ego of Vic Sage. Following Flashpoint, Question became an independent entity with a separate history.

Major Story Arcs

Trinity War

The Question approaches the imprisoned Superman and informs him that he was not, in fact responsible for the death of Doctor Light. He claims that Dr Psycho, who was present in Kahndaq at the time, may have been responsible. At his urging, Superman breaks out of containment, and they, together with several Justice League and Justice League of America members, search for and find Psycho. The villain denies involvement, and the group returns to ARGUS just in time for a massive explosion set by the Secret Society. He travels with the various Leagues to a temple near Athens where many other villains are fighting over Pandora's Box. He asks Pandora if opening the Box will finally answer his questions, but he is unable to take possession of the Box before The Outsider opens it, bringing the Crime Syndicate into the universe.

Forever Evil

Escaping the aftermath of the Crime Syndicate's arrival, Question returns to Hub City, where he is attacked by the Phantom Stranger. The pair fight, and Question transports them to the Mount of Olives, the site of the Stranger's great betrayal. He is nearly able to convince the Stranger to take his own life with the Spear of Inquisition, but is stopped by Zauriel, and vanishes. However, he is forcibly called to what appears to be the Rock of Eternity, where he and the other members of the Trinity of Sin are chained before John Constantine, Swamp Thing, and Nightmare Nurse. They manage to escape their bonds, and Question vanishes from the House of Mystery before Constantine can convince him to join their cause.

The Wages of Sin

Hidden away in an apparently ordinary life, Question is confronted by Ya'aka, a monster under the control of Nimraa. The monster kills his landlady, and attacks him, but he is pulled from the battle by his mystical bond with Pandora and the Stranger, who are also under attack. Angered, he disappears from the scene and returns to give his landlady a proper burial. However, Nimraa lures him to her side and uses him and the others to return Dark Earth to reality. The three briefly manage to escape, but are soon captured again. Question is held and tormented for some time before Pandora is able to rescue him. He joins the group in attempting to recover the Redemption Box, but, broken by his torture, he betrays them to Nimraa. Drawn into the Redemption Box with the others, he is the first to escape their bonds, as he is the only member of the group to doubt that he deserves punishment, and is able to rescue the others by gifting them with his doubt. He agrees to leave the Box along with the others, and joins in the confrontation with Queen Venna. He accepts the need to absorb all of the darkness of Dark Earth, and does so along with Pandora and the Stranger. When they have saved the world he attacks the others, apparently betraying them, but actually taking on their share of the darkness and sin.

Powers and Abilities

The Question appears to be a being of vast and largely unexplored supernatural power. He is functionally immortal, though it appears theoretically possible to kill him. He has shown the ability to teleport himself and others with apparently no limit regarding distance. He possesses an unexplained mental ability with which he can destabilize the minds of others by asking pointed questions; he may also possess a limited psychic ability. He is able to shapeshift or to project illusions around himself, allowing him to appear to be any person he wishes. He is completely faceless, but still capable of unimpeded sight and speech. He is a skilled fighter and detective.

Weapons and Equipment

The Question wields the Spear of Inquisition, a staff weapon with a blade at the end forged by his own hand from the Spear of Destiny. He is able to manifest this spear from an unknown location.

deck: A demon and former arch-duke of Hell who currently lives in New York City in the same apartment complex as John Constantine.
description:
Origin

Very little is known about Walter. A former arch-duke of Hell, he left for some unknown reason and moved to New York City. He sought employment with a cat rescue.

Creation

Walter was created by James Tynion IV, Ming Doyle, and Riley Rossmo. He made his first appearance in Constantine: The Hellblazer #6.

Major Story Arcs

The Hellblazer

Walter is attacked by Mister Gobble, the thing living in the basement of his apartment complex, and saved by John Constantine. Later, he orders some food from Oliver.

Powers and Abilities

Walter is a demon, and possesses all of the powers and skills inherent to his race, though he does not appear to be particularly powerful. He is a shape-shifter; the exact limits of his ability are unknown.
name: Walter
